<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910729-0126</DOCNO><DOCID>910729-0126.</DOCID><HL>   International:   Two Asian Agencies,   U.S. Group to Buy   25% of Chinese Bank   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/29/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5E</SO><CO>   J.LTC</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CHINA (CH)FAR EAST (FE)HONG KONG (HK)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   HONG KONG -- The Asian Development Bank, together withLong-Term Credit Bank of Japan and a closely held U.S. group,has agreed to buy 25% of Xiamen International Bank for 200million Hong Kong dollars (US$25.8 million).   Pending approval by the People's Bank of China, the AsianDevelopment Bank will buy 10% of Xiamen International,China's only joint-venture bank. Long-Term Credit is to takeanother 10%, while 5% is to be purchased by Sino FinanceGroup Ltd., which is controlled by WSGP Partners, a limitedpartnership led by former U.S. Treasury Secretary WilliamSimon and Gerald Parsky.</LP><TEXT>   Xiamen International, which opened in late 1985, iscurrently 49% held by Min Xin Holdings Ltd., a Hong Konglisted investment group with mainland connections. Its othermain owners are three state-owned groups in Fujian Province,the coastal jurisdiction containing the Xiamen specialeconomic zone.   Wu Hui Dong, the bank's chairman, said the investment willpromote the group's expansion plans.   &quot;Our bank shall continue to internationalize andcontribute to towards the economic prosperity and stabilityof China, Fujian Province, Hong Kong and Macao,&quot; he said.   The bank, which has 19 branches, had total assets ofHK$2.96 billion at the end of last year.The issue of newshares raises its paid-up capital to HK$620 million.</TEXT></DOC>